'''Scout Taylor-Compton''' born in California, is an American actress whose film credits include ''[[Love's Unfolding Dream]]'', ''[[An American Crime]]'', ''[[Wicked Little Things]]'', ''[[Tomorrow Is Today (2006 film)|Tomorrow is Today]]'' and ''[[Sleepover (2004 film)|Sleepover]]''.

Scout Taylor-Compton began acting at the age of 8 with a featured role in the A.F.I. film A.W.O.L. starring David Morse. Since then, her performances in ten independent films formed a firm foundation that led to her leading role in “An American Crime,” which stars Ellen Page and Catherine Keener.  Prior to “An American Crime,” Scout completed leading roles in Lifetime’s “Nasty,” Sony’s “The Children,” Lumiere Media’s “Tomorrow is Today,” which is currently being considered by Sony, and MGM’s “Sleepover.”

Scout’s television resume includes series regular roles in the Lifetime Series “Class Actions,” as well as Bravo’s “Hidden Howie,” starring Howie Mandel.  Other television guest credits include recurring roles on "Unfabulous," "The Guardian," "Charmed," and "Gilmore Girls," plus appearances on “Cold Case,” "The Division," "The Lyon's Den," "ER," "Ally McBeal," “The Tonight Show,” “That’s So Raven,” "Without a Trace," and most recently "Standoff."

Scout also trains with top coaches in acting, dance, and voice. When time permits, Scout continues to record for her debut album, as well as participates in charity projects for disabled and disadvantaged children. Her hobbies and interests include screenwriting, song writing, drums, hanging out with her friends, and her new Chihuahua puppy “Lexi.”


